In CSS, pseudo-elements are used to style a part of an HTML element, rather than the entire element. They are used to add a visual effect to a specific part of an element, such as the first letter, first line, or selection of text.

Pseudo-elements are denoted by a double colon (`::`) followed by the name of the pseudo-element. For example, `::first-letter` or `::selection`.

Here are some common pseudo-elements:

1. **`::first-letter`**: styles the first letter of a block-level element.
2. **`::first-line`**: styles the first line of a block-level element.
3. **`::before`**: adds content before an element.
4. **`::after`**: adds content after an element.
5. **`::selection`**: styles the selected text.
6. **`::placeholder`**: styles the placeholder text in a form input.

Pseudo-elements can be used to create a variety of visual effects, such as:

* Creating a drop cap (a large first letter) at the beginning of a paragraph.
* Highlighting the first line of a paragraph.
* Adding an icon or image before or after an element.
* Changing the background color or text color of selected text.
* Styling the placeholder text in a form input.

